# Day 37 ‚Äî MFA vs 2FA (and common bypasses)

## ‚úÖ What is 2FA?
2FA = Two different factors used to login.
Example:
- Password (something you know)
- OTP on phone (something you have)

## ‚úÖ What is MFA?
MFA = Multi-factor authentication (2 or more factors).
2FA is a type of MFA.

## üî• Factors of Authentication
1) Something you know ‚Üí password / PIN  
2) Something you have ‚Üí phone / OTP / authenticator app  
3) Something you are ‚Üí fingerprint / face  
(Extra: somewhere you are ‚Üí location sometimes)

## ‚úÖ Stronger MFA options (best ‚Üí ok)
‚úÖ Passkeys / FIDO2 Security Key (best)  
‚úÖ Authenticator App (TOTP)  
‚úÖ Push approvals (ok but risky)  
‚ö†Ô∏è SMS OTP (weakest)

## ‚ö†Ô∏è Real-world bypasses (how attackers still break MFA)
- **Phishing OTPs** (fake login pages steal OTP)
- **MFA fatigue attacks** (spam push notifications until user clicks yes)
- **SIM swapping** (take control of your phone number ‚Üí steal SMS OTP)
- **Session hijacking** (steal login session cookie after MFA)
- **Social engineering** (tricking support staff to reset MFA)

## ‚úÖ Best Practices (defense)
- Prefer **passkeys / authenticator app**
- Use **anti-phishing login pages**
- Enable **device binding** and **trusted devices**
- Use **short session lifetime + secure cookies**
- Monitor suspicious login attempts & alerts

‚úÖ Summary: MFA is strong, but not unbeatable. Real security comes from choosing strong MFA + securing sessions.
